Looking at the `[Symbol.match]` method:
```typescript
[Symbol.match] (string: string): RegExpMatchArray | null {
  if (string.length > 1 && string.endsWith('/')) {
    return null
  }
  return super[Symbol.match](string)
}
```

This is separate from the constructor validation. The mutation is only in the constructor.

Let me re-read the mutation very carefully:

Original: `if (spec.match(/^.+\/$/) !== null)`
Mutated: `if (spec.match(/.+\/$/) !== null)`

Both check if `spec` ends with `/`. The only difference is the `^` anchor.

For `/.+\/$/` to match when `/^.+\/$/` doesn't, we need a string where the pattern `.+\/` exists ending at `$` but NOT starting from position 0.

This is impossible if `.` matches the first character. Since `.` matches everything except `\n`, and `\n` is already forbidden...

